mpatible fetch/error contracts for the same workflow.","related_files":["calculate_wmi_rawseason_2010_11_to_2023_24.py","calculate_wmi_rawseason_2024_25.py","nba_pbp_utils.py"],"evidence":["calculate_wmi_rawseason_2010_11_to_2023_24.py:83-103 returns (status, payload) from fetch_game_json_with_retry(), using string sentinels like \"ok\" and \"missing\".","calculate_wmi_rawseason_2010_11_to_2023_24.py:152-170 wraps that again in a dict with another \"status\" field, so callers branch on status strings.","calculate_wmi_rawseason_2024_25.py:26-41 instead retries load_game_dataframe() by catching RETRYABLE_PIPELINE_ERRORS and re-raising on exhaustion.","calculate_wmi_rawseason_2024_25.py:44-73 then uses None as the signal for a non-usable game, while collect_parallel_tables() also catches exceptions separately at lines 109-116."],"suggestion":"Pick one public contract for game loading across the pipeline, such as a typed result object or a single exception-based API, and route both season scripts through that shared boundary so callers do not have to remember different failure shapes.","confidence":"high","impact_scope":"subsystem","fix_scope":"multi_file_refactor","root_cause_cluster":"pipeline_contract_drift"},{"dimension":"api_surface_coherence","identifier":"tuple_based_team_context_api","summary":"extract_team_context() exposes a positional tuple that makes callers rely on argument order.","related_files":["nba_pbp_utils.py","step2_build_possessions.py","build_possession_model_table_okc_mil.py","calculate_wmi_rawseason_2024_25.py"],"evidence":["nba_pbp_utils.py:93-101 returns tuple[dict[int, str], dict[int, int], list[int]] with no named fields.","step2_build_possessions.py:30 unpacks all three values positionally into team_id_to_tricode, opponent_id, team_ids.","calculate_wmi_rawseason_2024_25.py:52 discards the first item with _, opponent_id, team_ids, showing that callers only need parts of the tuple but still must remember its order.","build_possession_model_table_okc_mil.py:22 and categorize_defensive_fouls_okc_mil.py:23 repeat the same positional unpacking pattern, so a changed return order would silently break multiple modules."],"suggestion":"Replace the raw tuple with a small named result type, such as a dataclass or NamedTuple with fields like team_id_to_tricode, opponent_id, and team_ids, so callers can access only the fields they need by name.","confidence":"high","impact_scope":"subsystem","fix_scope":"multi_file_refactor","root_cause_cluster":"unnamed_boundary_data"},{"dimension":"api_surface_coherence","identifier":"pipeline_steps_take_mixed_input_shapes","summary":"Similar pipeline steps alternate between raw game IDs and prebuilt DataFrames as public inputs.","related_files":["step2_build_possessions.py","build_possession_model_table_okc_mil.py","categorize_defensive_fouls_okc_mil.py","calculate_wmi_rawgame_okc_mil.py"],"evidence":["step2_build_possessions.py:23-104 defines parse_possessions(pbp_df, game_id=...) and expects the caller to provide a play-by-play DataFrame.","build_possession_model_table_okc_mil.py:20-84 defines build_table(game_id) and performs its own fetch internally for a nearby transformation step.","categorize_defensive_fouls_okc_mil.py:21-104 follows the same game_id-based style, while calculate_wmi_rawgame_okc_mil.py:9-46 switches again to calculate_wmi_rawgame(df) over an already-shaped possession table.","Because these functions sit on adjacent pipeline stages but expose different boundary shapes, a developer cannot predict whether a helper wants identifiers, raw actions, or DataFrames without opening the file."],"suggestion":"Define one composable pipeline convention for public helpers, for example pure transformation functions that take DataFrames plus thin CLI wrappers that fetch/load files, and apply it consistently across these scripts.","confidence":"medium","impact_scope":"subsystem","fix_scope":"multi_file_refactor","root_cause_cluster":"pipeline_contract_drift"}],"retrospectiv